92
00:05:12,097 --> 00:05:14,615
So this genetic variant actually really
common.

93
00:05:14,615 --> 00:05:17,623
So it's much more common to get a positive
result from this test then from a,

94
00:05:17,623 --> 00:05:19,020
then to get a negative test.

95
00:05:19,020 --> 00:05:20,990
But the specificity here was 26%.

96
00:05:20,990 --> 00:05:24,540
In other words, there were 148 false
positives.

97
00:05:24,540 --> 00:05:29,450
148 women out of the control group falsely
tested positive on this test.

98
00:05:29,450 --> 00:05:30,970
So that's the sensitivity and specificity.

99
00:05:30,970 --> 00:05:33,970
And if you to the company website, they
have a nice little brochure,

100
00:05:33,970 --> 00:05:37,210
where they lay out the calculation of
sensitivity and specificity for you.

101
00:05:37,210 --> 00:05:38,930
And they did it correctly.

102
00:05:40,630 --> 00:05:43,350
What's really fun about this problem, is,
if I ask you

103
00:05:43,350 --> 00:05:46,940
to calculate the positive predictive
value, it's actually a little bit tricky.

104
00:05:46,940 --> 00:05:50,740
So this is a really good exercise, I
think, because if I just give you

105
00:05:50,740 --> 00:05:54,070
the data in the two by two table, when I
give this to students and I say,

106
00:05:54,070 --> 00:05:58,970
calculate the positive predictive value,
everybody's tempted to say, oh well,

107
00:05:58,970 --> 00:06:03,950
there were 316 people who tested positive,
168 of them actually have cellulite.

108
00:06:03,950 --> 00:06:05,880
So that's the positive predictive value.

109
00:06:05,880 --> 00:06:09,170
That is in fact incorrect, okay?

110
00:06:09,170 --> 00:06:11,860
So why is that not correct?

111
00:06:11,860 --> 00:06:14,410
It's, keep in mind, the study design here.

112
00:06:14,410 --> 00:06:16,820
This is a case controlled study.

113
00:06:16,820 --> 00:06:20,750
So the prevalence of the condition, of
having moderate to severe cellulite,

114
00:06:20,750 --> 00:06:25,280
is different in the study sample, than it
is in the general population.

115
00:06:25,280 --> 00:06:29,540
And remember, positive predictive value
depends on the prevalence of disease.

116
00:06:29,540 --> 00:06:34,220
So we have to factor in, the actual
prevalence of the disease in the general

117
00:06:34,220 --> 00:06:38,680
population here in order to calculate
positive predictive value, for this test.

118
00:06:38,680 --> 00:06:39,700
So that's a little tricky.

119
00:06:40,890 --> 00:06:45,530
To the company's credit if you go read
their little brochure they say,

120
00:06:45,530 --> 00:06:48,970
oh well they knew they had to incorporate
the actual prevalence.

121
00:06:48,970 --> 00:06:50,800
They must have a statistician involved.

122
00:06:50,800 --> 00:06:53,050
So they say, oh yeah we used Bayes' rule
to calculate it.

123
00:06:53,050 --> 00:06:56,860
So indeed they used Bayes' rule to
incorporate the true prevalence of

124
00:06:56,860 --> 00:06:58,050
cellulite in the population.

125
00:06:58,050 --> 00:07:01,970
So, that's a great example of where Bayes'
Rule can be useful.

126
00:07:01,970 --> 00:07:03,138
So let's actually do this.

127
00:07:03,138 --> 00:07:06,880
Let's use Bayes' Rule to calculate the
positive predictive value,

128
00:07:06,880 --> 00:07:11,470
incorporating the true prevalence of
cellulite in the population.

129
00:07:11,470 --> 00:07:15,600
So the company said that the true
prevalence of moderate cellulite in

130
00:07:15,600 --> 00:07:16,150
women was 65%.

131
00:07:16,150 --> 00:07:20,490
That sounds reasonable to me, so we'll
assume that's, that's reasonable.

132
00:07:20,490 --> 00:07:22,730
So now we can use Bayes' Rule to
incorporate that.

133
00:07:22,730 --> 00:07:25,621
Notice that that's higher then in case
control study where's its only 50%.

134
00:07:27,050 --> 00:07:29,310
So, let's, here's how we would apply
Bayes' rule.

135
00:07:29,310 --> 00:07:31,040
We want to know the positive predictive
value.

136
00:07:31,040 --> 00:07:35,790
We want to know the probability that you
will get moderate to severe cellulite,

137
00:07:35,790 --> 00:07:37,630
if you test positive on this test.

138
00:07:39,920 --> 00:07:41,560
Well, we can just apply Bayes' rule here,
so

139
00:07:41,560 --> 00:07:45,672
that's going to be equal to the posit,
probability of testing positive,

140
00:07:45,672 --> 00:07:50,510
given that you actually are a woman who's
going to get cellulite,

141
00:07:50,510 --> 00:07:54,280
times the marginal probability of getting
cellulite, that's the prevalence in

142
00:07:54,280 --> 00:07:58,220
the population, over the marginal
probability of testing positive at all.

143
00:07:58,220 --> 00:07:59,410
Alright.
So what's the probability that you're

144
00:07:59,410 --> 00:08:01,220
going to test positive given that you are
positive?

145
00:08:01,220 --> 00:08:02,690
Well, that's the sensitivity of the test.

146
00:08:02,690 --> 00:08:04,331
We just saw that that was 84%.

147
00:08:06,280 --> 00:08:09,550
What's the margin of probability of having
moderate to severe cellulite?

148
00:08:09,550 --> 00:08:13,020
The company just told us that that's 65%
in the general population,

149
00:08:13,020 --> 00:08:16,230
so that's where we're incorporating that
number.

150
00:08:16,230 --> 00:08:18,440
What's the marginal probability of testing
positive?

151
00:08:18,440 --> 00:08:20,660
Well, there are two ways you could test
positive.

152
00:08:20,660 --> 00:08:23,050
You could be one of those of 65% of women,

153
00:08:23,050 --> 00:08:25,360
who actually has moderate to severe
cellulite, or

154
00:08:25,360 --> 00:08:31,250
is going to get it and, your chance of
testing positive is 84%, the sensitivity.

155
00:08:31,250 --> 00:08:34,770
Or, you can be one of the 35% of women,

156
00:08:34,770 --> 00:08:37,630
who is not destined to get moderate to
severe cellulite.

157
00:08:37,630 --> 00:08:42,570
Your chance of testing positive on this
test is actually 74%.

158
00:08:42,570 --> 00:08:44,500
That's 1 minus the specificity.

159
00:08:44,500 --> 00:08:46,570
Remember the specificity was 26%.

160
00:08:46,570 --> 00:08:49,410
That means the false positive rate is 74%.

161
00:08:49,410 --> 00:08:53,160
So that's the marginal probability of
testing positive.

162
00:08:53,160 --> 00:08:58,670
When you add that up, it comes out to be
.805 in our denominator.

163
00:08:58,670 --> 00:09:00,710
So, we can put all these numbers together.

164
00:09:02,130 --> 00:09:06,732
So .84, times 0.65, that's equal to

165
00:09:06,732 --> 00:09:12,396
.546 we divide that by the denominator of
.805,

166
00:09:12,396 --> 00:09:18,285
we get that the positive predictive value
is 67.8%.

167
00:09:18,285 --> 00:09:20,865
All right, so the, the company calculated
that,

168
00:09:20,865 --> 00:09:24,885
in their literature, now in their
marketing material, they rounded that up,

169
00:09:24,885 --> 00:09:28,785
so they said, oh, your, the, the actual
probability that you're going to

170
00:09:28,785 --> 00:09:33,363
get moderate to severe cellulite if you
test positive is 60, it's about 68%.

171
00:09:33,363 --> 00:09:35,846
Well they said, they rounded that up to
approximately 70%.

172
00:09:35,846 --> 00:09:39,896
They were trying to boost it, make it
look, just look a little bit better.

173
00:09:39,896 --> 00:09:41,832
Okay.

174
00:09:41,832 --> 00:09:44,496
Now notice that that's an application of
Bayes' Rule.

175
00:09:44,496 --> 00:09:47,681
For those of you who are more comfortable
using the tree, which most students

176
00:09:47,681 --> 00:09:50,900
are when they first start this material,
you could also do this on the tree.

177
00:09:50,900 --> 00:09:52,800
So let me just quickly show you how to do
it on the tree.

178
00:09:52,800 --> 00:09:55,700
So, and then I'm going to show you how to
do it using a 2 by 2 table.

179
00:09:55,700 --> 00:09:57,790
I'm going to give you many ways to get the
right answer.

180
00:09:57,790 --> 00:10:00,750
And remember, with probability there's
many ways to get the right answer.

181
00:10:00,750 --> 00:10:02,510
Some are more efficient than others.

182
00:10:02,510 --> 00:10:04,770
Some are, are better for when you're
